---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
const title = 'Explore the pairs — Dual-marker discovery';
const description = 'TODO: an interactive explorer over the candidate surface-marker pairs, their tumor coverage, and their healthy-tissue liability.';
---
<Base title={title} description={description} page="explore">
  <section class="hero" style="padding-bottom:0.6rem">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">The tool</p>
      <h1>Explore the pairs</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        TODO: tell the reader what to do here and what to look for. The satmut version pointed the
        reader at a specific element and two specific bases, which is why it worked.
      </p>
      <div class="embed-bar">
        <a class="btn primary" href="/explorer.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open the explorer in a new tab &rarr;</a>
        <span class="pill">TODO: n patients · n pairs · n cell types</span>
      </div>
      <div class="todo">
        <p><b>Wiring.</b> <code>public/explorer.html</code> is built in the science repo and copied
        here by <code>build_image.sh</code>. Gitignored, so this page is blank until the first build.</p>
        <p><b>Design note.</b> The satmut explorer lazy-loaded one JSON per locus from
        <code>/snvs/&lt;name&gt;.json</code>. The equivalent here is one JSON per pair, or per
        patient, served from <code>/pairs/&lt;name&gt;.json</code>. Decide before writing the
        explorer, because the app's route and cache follow from it.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="block">
    <div class="container">
      <iframe class="embed" src="/explorer.html" title="Marker-pair explorer" loading="lazy" style="height:88vh"></iframe>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
